`template/scripts/` is the CI/lint gate suite and update tooling shipped into every scaffolded project — the contract with the rest of the codebase is that `ctx-verify` (or CI) invokes each check script and parses `FAIL: <path>:<line>: ...` lines from stdout/stderr, and that `update-template.sh` is the sole path for pulling fresh tooling from the upstream CTX repo.

All checks (`cycle_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, `retired_terms_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) share the same file-enumeration convention — `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard`, never a filesystem walk — specifically to avoid racing concurrent writers into `target/` and to respect gitignore. They also share the `path:line:message` diagnostic shape (grep's `-H` plus trailing `/dev/null` to force the prefix even on single-file matches), which `ctx-verify`'s `split_loc` parser depends on; changing that output shape in one script without checking the parser breaks the whole suite silently. Several are explicit MVP placeholders for future dylint rules (`cycle_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`) — they scaffold the check's presence in CI without full correctness.

The generator scripts form a separate pipeline: `gen_tool_contracts.sh` regenerates the tool-contracts block in `CLAUDE.md` from `--contract` output of built binaries, `gen_readme_architecture.sh` (repo-only, not shipped to scaffolded projects) splices `.context/rollup.ctx` into README.md, and both share the same `--write`/`--check` marker-replacement shape and `FAIL:`-emitting `--check` mode. Marker strings in `gen_tool_contracts.sh` must stay byte-identical to what `update-template.sh` greps for when splicing `CLAUDE.md` on sync — editing one without the other breaks the sync silently.

`install-tools.sh` builds the `ctx-*` binaries every check and generator script assumes exist at `target/debug/`; `update-template.sh` calls it, then mirrors a hardcoded file list (configs, check scripts, prompts) from the upstream CTX repo, and finally invokes the `gen_tool_contracts.sh` splice — it syncs itself last since Bash can't safely rewrite a running script mid-execution. The mirror lists in `update-template.sh` are the single point of truth for "what counts as pure tooling vs. project-owned"; adding a new check script here requires updating that array too.